SALMONELLOSIS, SEROTYPE PARATYPHI B - USA (04): (NORTH CAROLINA), TEMPEH
************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 8 May 2012
Source: Greenville Online [edited]
http://www.greenvilleonline.com/article/20120508/NEWS/305080028/


The number of cases in a Buncombe County salmonellosis outbreak surged 30 percent over the weekend [5-6 May 2012], county health officials said Mon 7 May 2012. Government food and health regulators are zeroing in on a tempeh ingredient sold by a Maryland company as the possible source of the bacterial infection. The FDA is now among the agencies involved in the investigation of ingredients in the cultured bean product.

It appears that some of the people newly sickened were exposed to the bacteria together, possibly at parties, County Health Director Gibbie Harris said. "We don't know at this point because we are starting to do the interviews, but it is a possibility that it is a combination of food and person-to-person exposure," she said.

On Mon 7 May 2012, agriculture officials said they found salmonellae in a starter culture that Smiling Hara buys from a Rockville, Maryland, distributor. The state's Health and Human Services Department is now testing to see whether it is the same type of the bacterium found in the outbreak.

None of Smiling Hara's 6 employees had been sick, leading officials to believe the bacterium came from an ingredient. Along with the culture, there are 2 other ingredients: vinegar and beans either soy, black, or black-eyed peas.

[Byline: Joel Burgess]

